=== Lesson 26-2 (Step-by-Step Approach) ===

 {"type":"h3","text":"Step-by-Step Approach"}
 {"type":"h4","text":"Step 1: Isolate the Original Relationship & State It Abstractly"}
 {"type":"paragraph","text":"Go to the specific scenario in the passage. Identify its key components..."}
 {"type":"list","items":["**Example:** If the passage describes a tool created for scientific research that becomes popular as a children's toy, your abstract rule is: \"X is designed for a serious purpose but becomes widely used for an unintended, recreational one.\""]}

{ "type": "diff-note", "text": "The scientific-tool-to-toy example is concrete and well-chosen. It cleanly demonstrates the abstraction process.", "variant": "comment" }

 {"type":"h4","text":"Step 2: Test Each Answer Choice Against Your Abstract Rule"}
 {"type":"paragraph","text":"...Be ruthless—eliminate any choice that has extra components, missing pieces, or a different sequence of events..."}
+{{+**Missing:** Add a concrete elimination example. E.g., "If a choice describes a tool created for fun that is later used for research, the direction is reversed -- eliminate it."+}}
+{{+**Try this:** Attempt the question before reading the analysis below.+}}
+{{+Add a question-card here demonstrating the full abstract-and-match method.+}}
 {"type":"hr"}
 {"type":"h3","text":"If You Get Stuck Between Two Choices..."}
 {"type":"h4","text":"Tie-Breaker #1: The Reverse Test"}
 {"type":"paragraph","text":"Take one of your strong contenders and treat it as the original scenario..."}
 {"type":"h4","text":"Tie-Breaker #2: Focus on the Difference"}
 {"type":"paragraph","text":"Stop looking at how your final two choices are similar to the original..."}
+{{+**Missing:** This module lacks a trap/distractor section. Common analogy traps include: (1) Topic-matching -- same subject matter but different structural logic; (2) Partial match -- some components match but others are missing or altered; (3) Reversed direction -- same components but causal direction is flipped. Consider adding a brief section here or a separate Lesson 26-3.+}}

{ "type": "diff-note", "text": "The two tie-breaker strategies are genuinely useful. The Reverse Test (checking if the answer and original are interchangeable blueprints) is an especially elegant heuristic.", "variant": "comment" }
